I guess  this was inevitable:

Ozy Media Chief Executive Carlos Watson was arrested Thursday morning after=
 a former executive with whom he founded the embattled startup pleaded guil=
ty to fraud charges in a secretive federal court proceeding.
Mr. Watson was taken into custody and is expected to be arraigned in a Broo=
klyn, N.Y., federal court on charges of conspiring to commit securities fra=
ud and conspiring to commit wire fraud, according to a law-enforcement offi=
cial. Ozy came under federal scrutiny for its business practices after the =
New York Times reported in 2021 that its then-chief operating officer, Sami=
r Rao, impersonated an executive of Alphabet Inc.=E2=80=99s YouTube during =
a fundraising call with Goldman Sachs Group Inc.=C2=A0
=E2=80=9CWe are really disappointed,=E2=80=9D Lanny Breuer, Mr. Watson=E2=
=80=99s lawyer, said of his client=E2=80=99s arrest. =E2=80=9CWe have been =
acting in good faith and believe we had a constructive dialogue with the go=
vernment and are shocked by the actions this morning.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
Mr. Rao pleaded guilty Tuesday in Brooklyn federal court to fraud and ident=
ity theft charges, under a court-approved John Doe pseudonym. He admitted t=
o a U.S. magistrate judge that between 2018 and 2021 he made misleading sta=
tements to investors and inflated the company=E2=80=99s financial performan=
ce. He also said he falsely used the identity of another person without the=
 authority to do so between February 2020 and February 2021.=C2=A0

We   talked in 2021 about the time that Rao impersonated a YouTube executiv=
e on a due diligence call with Goldman. =E2=80=9COrdinarily if I were telli=
ng you this story,=E2=80=9D I wrote,=C2=A0=E2=80=9CI=E2=80=99d be quoting f=
rom a federal criminal complaint, or at least a Securities and Exchange Com=
mission enforcement action, but nope everything is fine!=E2=80=9D Well, now=
 there is  a federal criminal case, and also an SEC enforcement action.=C2=
=A0From the  prosecutors=E2=80=99 announcement:

An indictment was unsealed this morning in federal court in Brooklyn chargi=
ng OZY Media Inc. (Ozy), a media and entertainment company headquartered in=
 Mountain View, California, and its founder and Chief Executive Officer, Ca=
rlos Watson, with conspiracy to commit securities fraud and conspiracy to c=
ommit wire fraud in connection with a scheme to defraud Ozy=E2=80=99s inves=
tors and lenders by making material misrepresentations about Ozy=E2=80=99s =
financial and business assets. =C2=A0Watson is also charged with aggravated=
 identity theft for his role in the impersonation of multiple media company=
 executives in communications with Ozy=E2=80=99s lenders and prospective in=
vestors in furtherance of the fraud schemes.=C2=A0 =E2=80=A6
=E2=80=9CAs alleged, Carlos Watson is a con man whose business strategy was=
 based on outright deceit and fraud =E2=80=93 he ran Ozy as a criminal orga=
nization rather than as a reputable media company,=E2=80=9D stated United S=
tates Attorney Peace. =C2=A0=E2=80=9CInvestment fraud undermines confidence=
 in our nation=E2=80=99s markets and investors and makes it harder for hone=
st businesses to compete. =C2=A0Our Office and the Department of Justice ha=
ve made it clear that prosecuting corporations and their corrupt executives=
 who flagrantly violate the law are top priorities.=E2=80=9D
=E2=80=9CAs the indictment today alleges, Watson repeatedly attempted to en=
tice both investors and lenders through a series of deliberate deceptions a=
nd fabrications. =C2=A0The FBI and our partners in law enforcement will hol=
d any individual willing to defraud investors and financial institutions ac=
countable in the criminal justice system,=E2=80=9D stated Assistant Directo=
r-in-Charge Driscoll.

=E2=80=9CHis role in the impersonation of multiple media company executives=
=E2=80=9D!? Multiple? What? Here=E2=80=99s the other one:
In December 2019, Watson and his co-conspirators attempted to induce a bank=
 to lend Ozy money based on misrepresentations and omissions about Ozy=E2=
=80=99s business. =C2=A0Watson and his co-conspirators sought to secure the=
 loan with anticipated revenues from a second season of an Ozy television s=
how. =C2=A0However, the contract between Ozy and the show=E2=80=99s cable n=
etwork for the second season of the show was still under negotiation. =C2=
=A0To induce the bank to make the loan sooner, Watson directed Ozy=E2=80=99=
s then-Chief Financial Officer (CFO) to send the bank a fake signed contrac=
t between Ozy and the cable network purporting to be for the second season.=
 =C2=A0When the then-CFO refused, Rao, with Watson=E2=80=99s approval, sent=
 the fake contract =E2=80=94 which contained terms favorable to Ozy and a f=
orged signature =E2=80=94 to the bank, copying the then-CFO. =C2=A0Later th=
at day, the then-CFO emailed Watson and Rao to say that she was resigning e=
ffective immediately. =C2=A0She explained, =E2=80=9Cthis . . . is illegal. =
=C2=A0This is fraud. =C2=A0This is forging someone=E2=80=99s signature with=
 the intent of getting an advance from a publicly traded bank.=E2=80=9D =C2=
=A0She continued, =E2=80=9CTo be crystal clear, what you see as a measured =
risk =E2=80=94 I see as a felony.=E2=80=9D
I mean, yes, but I am a little confused that she sent that email in 2019 an=
d the charges are only coming in 2023? Like if you send that email to your =
boss on the way out the door, isn=E2=80=99t your next stop at the SEC to ge=
t a whistleblower deal? Also here is this about the YouTube call:
On or about February 2, 2021, Rao had a call with employees of the financia=
l institution during which he impersonated a media executive from the onlin=
e video service using a voice alteration application that he downloaded ont=
o his cellular telephone to mask his voice during the call. =C2=A0During th=
e call, Watson was in the same room as Rao, and texted Rao instructions abo=
ut what to say and what not to say on the call. =C2=A0Shortly after the cal=
l, one of the employees of the financial institution contacted the actual m=
edia executive of the online video service, who confirmed that he had not b=
een on the call and that the online video service had no role in the produc=
tion of The Carlos Watson Show. =C2=A0When members of the financial institu=
tion later spoke with Watson, he falsely claimed that Rao had acted alone a=
nd as a result of a mental breakdown.
The indictment  describes the text messages:
Throughout the call, the defendant CARLOS WATSON sent a series of text mess=
ages to Rao, which included instructions of what to say and not say. For ex=
ample, at approximately 11:19 a.m. (EST), WATSON texted Rao, 'i am a big fa=
n of Carlos, Samir and the show." At approximately 11:21 a.m. (EST), WATSON=
 texted Rao, "Use the right pronouns ... You are NOT OZY." At approximately=
 11:26 a.m. (EST), after Rao had repeatedly used the first name of one of t=
he employees of Financial Institution 1 who was on the call, WATSON texted =
Rao, "Stop using her name."
I guess Rao kept saying =E2=80=9Cwe=E2=80=9D when he meant =E2=80=9COzy=E2=
=80=9D? Which an actual YouTube executive would not say? And he kept addres=
sing the Goldman employee by name, because he is a salesperson (and a forme=
r Goldman employee himself), but of course an actual YouTube executive hopp=
ing on a random diligence call probably wouldn=E2=80=99t even know her name=
? Not so easy to impersonate people, is it?
Those are just the=C2=A0impersonation=C2=A0charges, but there are various m=
ore normal sorts of alleged fraud too. Watson  allegedly told a broker =E2=
=80=9Cthat a well-known hedge fund manager =E2=80=A6=C2=A0had already commi=
tted a $5 million investment=E2=80=9D to Ozy=E2=80=99s Series C round; the =
manager was actually in the round but for just under $1 million. A pitch de=
ck allegedly =E2=80=9Cstated that Ozy=E2=80=99s 2018 revenue was $22 millio=
n when, in fact, it was about $10 million, and that certain well-known inve=
stors were =E2=80=98leading=E2=80=99 the Series C round, when they were not=
.=E2=80=9D In the Series D round, Watson and Rao allegedly told the broker =
=E2=80=9Cthat a television star=E2=80=99s company and a famous live enterta=
inment company would be leading the round,=E2=80=9D when they were not inve=
stors at all.=C2=A0In the pitch to Goldman, they sent a deck that allegedly=
 =E2=80=9Cinflated Ozy=E2=80=99s earnings before interest, taxes, depreciat=
ion, and amortization (=E2=80=98EBITDA=E2=80=99) numbers by over 70% for 20=
18 and approximately 80% for 2019.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
One thing that we   talk about=C2=A0sometimes=C2=A0around here is that ther=
e is probably a certain leeway for private companies to, uh, exaggerate sli=
ghtly in their fundraising pitches. Not legal advice or anything! But the i=
nvestors kind of expect it: They=C2=A0want=C2=A0visionary, envelope-pushing=
, see-the-world-not-as-it-is-but-as-it-could-be founders, so they are willi=
ng to tolerate some founders who are not constrained by reality, and to wri=
te off fraud losses as =E2=80=9Cwell, lots of startups fail.=E2=80=9D Plus =
the audience for startup pitches is smaller than that for public companies,=
 and the investors don=E2=80=99t want to be embarrassed: If you got hoodwin=
ked by a startup, it doesn=E2=80=99t really do much for your reputation to =
go around complaining about it loudly.
Is Ozy the first private company to send an investor a pitch deck that infl=
ated its Ebitda by 70% or 80%? Probably not, no. But in recent years there =
does seem to have been a bit of a crackdown on private-company securities f=
raud. Some of that is due to   the influence of Theranos, I think, and some=
 of it is just that private markets are bigger and more important than they=
 used to be. =E2=80=9CPrivate markets are the new public markets,=E2=80=9D =
I sometimes say, and if you can raise billions of dollars from big institut=
ions in private markets then you probably will get treated more like a publ=
ic company.
Also the main thing is probably just that if you do a fraud that is so egre=
gious and hilarious that it becomes national news, you will get in trouble.=
 If you are marking up your Ebitda a bit in pitches to private investors, p=
rosecutors and the SEC might never hear about it, but if you are doing mult=
iple elaborate impersonations to raise money you are eventually going to at=
tract attention.

