<table class=3D"header" width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" cellp=
adding=3D"0">
<tr>
<td class=3D"body-header-container" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; mso=
-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Are NFTs securities?</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Imagine a video game. There=E2=80=99s an onlin=
e multiplayer video game, MattQuest, made and run by a video-game company, =
QuestCo. In the game you play a character, and the character can wear a hat=
. QuestCo periodically releases exciting new limited-edition hats for chara=
cters, which you can buy, from the company, with real money. You give them =
your credit card and they bill you $10 and now your character has a purple =
hat or whatever. Some hats are common and cheap; others are rare and expens=
ive.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">There is an active secondary market for hats, =
in which players can sell the hats they own or buy hats from others, for re=
al money. This market is administered by QuestCo, and QuestCo does not allo=
w trading outside of its own platform. So someone who has a rare teal hat m=
ight list it for sale for $1,000, and if you covet that hat for your charac=
ter you can pay $1,000 for it. You use your credit card or a bank transfer =
to put $1,000 into your account at QuestCo, and then you click to buy the h=
at, and QuestCo=C2=A0takes the $1,000 out of your account and transfers it =
to the seller=E2=80=99s account. Actually QuestCo collects a 5% fee on the =
trade, so the seller gets $950. She gets $950 in her QuestCo account, that =
is. If she wants to take that money out =E2=80=94=C2=A0to put it in her ban=
k account =E2=80=94=C2=A0QuestCo will send her a bank transfer, but it will=
 take another fee for cashing her out. Also maybe there will be a delay of =
a few weeks between when she asks to withdraw the money and when she gets i=
t. QuestCo is a video-game company, not a=C2=A0bank, and it might not be su=
per-efficient at processing withdrawals.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The more popular the game is, and the more act=
ive and successful the company is at promoting the value of having a cool h=
at for your character, the more valuable the hats will be. If you buy a bur=
gundy hat on the secondary market for $20, and then MattQuest becomes vastl=
y more popular and lots of celebrities go on talk shows to talk about how t=
hey covet a burgundy=C2=A0hat for their MattQuest characters, then you migh=
t be able to resell your hat for $10,000. And then of course this will be s=
elf-reinforcing:=C2=A0<em>You=C2=A0</em>can go on talk shows, or at least Y=
ouTube,=C2=A0and talk about how you got rich trading MattQuest hats, and ot=
her people will see you and say =E2=80=9Chey I want that=E2=80=9D and buy=
=C2=A0hats and push the price still higher.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Are the hats =E2=80=9Csecurities,=E2=80=9D und=
er US law? The <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/306=
40231.258438/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9jb3JwZmluL2ZyYW1ld29yay1pbnZlc3RtZW=
50LWNvbnRyYWN0LWFuYWx5c2lzLWRpZ2l0YWwtYXNzZXRz/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB8eb=
2301f" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" sty=
le=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width=
: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background=
-color: #ccc;"> relevant definition</a> is the Howey test, which says that =
something is a security if =E2=80=9Cthere is the investment of money in a c=
ommon enterprise with a reasonable expectation of profits to be derived fro=
m the efforts of others.=E2=80=9D Here I think the analysis would go like:<=
/p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You invested money, by putting money =
into your account to buy hats.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The=
re is a common enterprise, in the sense that you and everyone else=C2=A0are=
=C2=A0giving the money to QuestCo, playing=C2=A0MattQuest and trading hats =
on the QuestCo-controlled market.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">=
There is=C2=A0<em>possibly=C2=A0</em>an expectation of profit, in the sense=
 that you might be buying the hats because you think the price will go up. =
This one is fuzzy, I think: Maybe you buy a hat because you think that it l=
ooks nice on your character. But=C2=A0if QuestCo is going around=C2=A0<em>t=
elling=C2=A0</em>everyone, like, =E2=80=9Cbuying MattQuest hats is a great =
way to fund your retirement, they have gone up by 18% every quarter=E2=80=
=9D or whatever, then that sounds like an expectation of profit.<a class=3D=
"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-1" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decorat=
ion: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #00000=
0; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !imp=
ortant; display: inline-block;">
<span>[1]</span>
</a>
</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The profits are derived from the =
efforts of others, in the sense that QuestCo is in charge of developing and=
 promoting the game, and the hats.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">So, I mean, I dunno, maybe. If the hats are se=
curities, then QuestCo has to register them with the US Securities and Exch=
ange Commission =E2=80=94=C2=A0meaning that it has to provide a lot of publ=
ic disclosure, including risk factors, audited financial statements, and ma=
nagement discussion of its business =E2=80=94=C2=A0if it wants to sell them=
 to the public in the US.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-2" s=
tyle=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-wid=
th: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important=
; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[2]</span>
</a> You might be interested in that disclosure! For instance, if you are a=
bout to transfer a million dollars into your QuestCo account to fund a hat-=
buying spree, you might want to take a look at QuestCo=E2=80=99s audited ba=
lance sheet and see how much money it has. If the balance sheet is like =E2=
=80=9CLIABILITIES: $100 million in customer hat accounts; ASSETS: some imag=
inary hats,=E2=80=9D you might worry. You might think thoughts like: =E2=80=
=9CWait, if they owe customers $100 million, do they actually have $100 mil=
lion in cash?=E2=80=9D Or=C2=A0like: =E2=80=9CWait, if I put my $1 million =
into QuestCo, and then do some profitable hat trading and end up with $3 mi=
llion, will I actually be able to cash it out?=E2=80=9D<a class=3D"footnote=
-index" href=3D"#footnote-3" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none=
 !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border=
-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; d=
isplay: inline-block;">
<span>[3]</span>
</a>=C2=A0The hats=C2=A0<em>are=C2=A0</em>an investment in QuestCo in the s=
ense that you give QuestCo money, and then you wait, and then you=C2=A0hope=
 it will give you back your money, so having some disclosure about its fina=
ncial circumstances would be useful.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I am not particularly a gamer, and I am also n=
ot actually a securities lawyer,=C2=A0but my vague sense is that (1) there =
are games that work kind of like this, (2) they do not register their in-ga=
me items as securities and (3) no one gets particularly worked up about tha=
t. You can see the argument that the hats are securities, but, you know. Th=
ey are hats in a video game. They don=E2=80=99t really <em>feel=C2=A0</em>l=
ike securities.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">On the other hand if you call the hats=C2=A0=
=E2=80=9Cnon-fungible tokens=E2=80=9D and replace the words =E2=80=9C$1,000=
 in your account at QuestCo=E2=80=9D with the words =E2=80=9C$1,000 worth o=
f tokens on the Quest blockchain,=E2=80=9D then:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">For like 15 minutes in 2021 you could=
 have sparked a speculative frenzy where the hats were selling for millions=
 of dollars; and</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">When the prices i=
nevitably crashed, people would inevitably sue you for securities fraud.</l=
i>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Those things are linked: The speculative frenz=
y is what made you all the money, but the speculative frenzy is also what c=
onvinced everyone that the hats were securities. NFTs were a new thing =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0though they were also kind of like hats in video games =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0which made people open to believing that they might be worth milli=
ons of dollars, but which=C2=A0<em>also=C2=A0</em>made people open to belie=
ving that they might be securities. And the main problem with securities is=
 that, if you sell them to the general public and you=C2=A0<em>don=E2=80=99=
t=C2=A0</em>register those sales, the buyers can demand their money back. I=
f you sold millions of dollars=E2=80=99 worth of unregistered securities du=
ring a huge bubble, and then the bubble popped, that=E2=80=99s bad.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Anyway, not hats, but <a href=3D"https://link.=
mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30640231.258438/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZX=
JnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDItMjIvbmJhLXRvcC1zaG90LW5mdHMtYXJlLXNlY=
3VyaXRpZXMtanVkZ2Utc2F5cy1pbi1sYW5kbWFyay1jYXNlP2NtcGlkPUJCRDAyMjMyM19NT05F=
WVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTI=
zMDIyMyZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBb579683f" =
itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"c=
olor: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; =
border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color:=
 #ccc;">  highlights of basketball games</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The creator of the National Basketball Associa=
tion=E2=80=99s Top Shot NFTs must face a lawsuit accusing it of selling unr=
egistered securities, marking a new development in a broader fight over how=
 to classify cryptoassets like nonfungible tokens.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In the suit, filed in 2021, purchasers of Top =
Shot Moments =E2=80=94 digital video clips of highlights from NBA games =E2=
=80=94 allege that Dapper Labs violated US securities law by offering the i=
tems without registering them with regulators and that Dapper improperly us=
ed its control over the popular collectibles.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">US District Judge Victor Marrero on Wednesday =
denied a request by Dapper to throw out the suit before trial, finding that=
 the plaintiffs had adequately alleged that Moments are securities for the =
case to go forward. Marrero said that the trading of Moments is limited to =
the company=E2=80=99s Flow blockchain and that purchasers therefore rely on=
 Dapper=E2=80=99s expertise and management =E2=80=9Cas well as its continue=
d existence.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CHypothetically, if Upper Deck or Topp=
s, two longtime producers of physical sports trading cards, were to go out =
of business, the value of the cards they sold would be wholly unaffected, a=
nd may even increase, much like posthumously discovered art,=E2=80=9D the j=
udge wrote.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">He continued: =E2=80=9CThat is not true here, =
where plaintiffs allege that the pooling of capital generated from the sale=
 of Moments propped up the Flow Blockchain and where the value of Moments i=
s intertwined with the success of that blockchain and Dapper Labs.=E2=80=9D=
</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here is <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloomberg=
business.com/click/30640231.258438/aHR0cHM6Ly9hc3NldHMuYndieC5pby9kb2N1bWVu=
dHMvdXNlcnMvaXFqV0hCRmRmeElVL3JOTDlTT1M5MVhnby92MA/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23c=
B71963d0e" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank"=
 style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-w=
idth: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backgr=
ound-color: #ccc;"> the opinion</a>, and I think it is worth noting how inv=
olved Dapper is in every part of the investment. Top Shot Moments are not n=
on-fungible tokens on some public third-party blockchain like Ethereum or S=
olana; instead, they exist on Dapper=E2=80=99s =E2=80=9Cown private blockch=
ain, Flow,=E2=80=9D <a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-4" style=
=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: =
1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; ba=
ckground-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[4]</span>
</a>though I suppose that characterization is debatable and <a href=3D"http=
s://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30640231.258438/aHR0cHM6Ly9kZWNye=
XB0LmNvLzgzOTU3L2Zsb3ctYmxvY2tjaGFpbi1jb250cm9sbGVkLWNvbW11bml0eS1kYXBwZXIt=
bGFicw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB8bbd7d3b" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=
=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: =
none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; bo=
rder-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> Dapper says that Flow i=
s now decentralized</a>. But the way you transfer money onto the Flow block=
chain to buy Top Shot Moments does seem to run through Dapper. Specifically=
 (citations omitted):</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Dapper Labs, which maintains a digital wallet,=
 called a =E2=80=9CDapper Wallet,=E2=80=9D for all users to facilitate paym=
ents, also takes a =E2=80=9Ccash-out fee=E2=80=9D when purchasers transfer =
their balance from the Dapper Wallet to their bank account.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Moments purchasers who sought to withdraw thei=
r cash off of the NBA Top Shot application have not always been able to do =
so, nor has it been quick. On March 26, 2021, Dapper Labs published on the =
NBA Top Shot website that withdrawals would first be enabled in six to eigh=
t weeks. Once=C2=A0enabled, Dapper Labs stated that withdrawals would be =
=E2=80=9Cprocessed within 21 days but others may take 40 days or more.=E2=
=80=9D=C2=A0Not all persons on the NBA Top Shot platform had withdrawal cap=
abilities enabled by Dapper Labs, and Plaintiffs allege that, even once Dap=
per Labs enabled the functionality, many were not able to withdraw their fu=
nds. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Plaintiffs also allege that purchasers=E2=80=
=99 capital is then held by Dapper Labs in Dapper-controlled wallets. Furth=
er, they contend that Dapper Labs has been retaining purchasers=E2=80=99 ca=
sh on its books for months after withdrawals are requested to help =E2=80=
=9Craise money at a high valuation,=E2=80=9D to =E2=80=9Cprop up the value =
of the [FLOW] token,=E2=80=9D because, without capital on the platform, =E2=
=80=9Cthe platform will collapse.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The point is that if you give money to a compa=
ny and the company says you got some return on your investment and you ask =
for your money back and the company keeps your money for as long as it feel=
s like, then that does feel more like an investment=C2=A0<em>in the company=
=C2=A0</em>than like a decentralized permissionless whatever. It is like my=
 MattQuest hats. You=E2=80=99d want to know things like, does Dapper have t=
he money?</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The rest of the opinion is fairly straightforw=
ard and along the lines we discussed for the hats: investment, common enter=
prise, expectation of profits, efforts of others. The =E2=80=9Cexpectation =
of profits=E2=80=9D prong is, I think, the weakest: What if you were just b=
uying these Moments because you love watching basketball highlights and you=
 want to =E2=80=9Cown,=E2=80=9D in some abstract sense, copies of limited e=
ditions of some of those highlights? But as with everything in crypto, ther=
e are awkward tweets where NBA Top Shot=E2=80=99s Twitter account promoted=
=C2=A0not the coolness of the highlight videos, but the amounts of money in=
volved in Top Shots trading. The opinion quotes some of them, and adds:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Each Tweet promotes a recent sale =
or statistics of recent sales of Moments on the Marketplace. And although t=
he literal word =E2=80=9Cprofit=E2=80=9D is not included in any of the Twee=
ts, the =E2=80=9Crocket ship=E2=80=9D emoji, =E2=80=9Cstock chart=E2=80=9D =
emoji, and =E2=80=9Cmoney bags=E2=80=9D emoji objectively mean one thing: a=
 financial return on investment.</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Well, there you go, a court ruling that the =
=E2=80=9Crocket ship=E2=80=9D emoji =E2=80=9Cobjectively mean[s] one thing:=
 a financial return on investment.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This is not a definitive ruling that these NFT=
s are securities =E2=80=94=C2=A0it is just a preliminary stage of the case =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0and it is certainly not a ruling that <em>all</em> NFTs are =
securities; the control that Dapper has over the investment here seems impo=
rtant. Also this is a case brought by private plaintiffs who bought Top Sho=
t Moments during the bubble, not the SEC; the SEC <a href=3D"https://link.m=
ail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30640231.258438/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJ=
nLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDItMTMvdGhlLXNlYy1jcmFja3MtZG93bi1vbi=
1jcnlwdG8_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDIyMzIzX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc=
291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjMwMjIzJnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm=
/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB6019a712" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"ite=
mscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !i=
mportant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bo=
ttom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  tends to think</a> that every=
thing is a security, but has <em>not </em>really=C2=A0gone around claiming =
that NFTs are securities.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-5" s=
tyle=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-wid=
th: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important=
; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[5]</span>
</a></p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But the main fact of crypto regulation in the =
US in 2023 is that the SEC is cracking down by saying that everything is a =
security, and some crypto businesses are pushing back, arguing in court tha=
t in fact=C2=A0<em>not </em>everything in crypto is a security. My assumpti=
on is that, especially after the crypto collapse last year, courts are goin=
g to be very sympathetic to the SEC=E2=80=99s arguments, and very inclined =
to believe that everything is a security. This decision=C2=A0is another sig=
n of that.</p>
